data.content:
Here's the full performance analysis for `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`, with all code treated as hot-path per your stated workload (millions of log entries/minute).

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.IndexOf(string)` no StringComparison | 0 |
| `.Substring(` | 0 |
| `.StartsWith/.EndsWith` no StringComparison | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()` | 1 |
| Chained `.Replace(` 3+ | 0 |
| `params` in signatures | 1 |
| LINQ `.Select/.Where/.Take/.Aggregate` | 12 |
| `.Any/.All` | 1 |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 |
| Unsealed non-abstract non-static classes | 1 |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| `new Regex(` | 0 |
| `Regex.Compiled` | 0 |

✅ No regex, no Substring, no HttpClient, no JSON serialization patterns detected.

---

## Findings

#### 1. Enum.ToString() + ToLowerInvariant() allocates 2 strings per unit 🔴
**Impact:** 2 heap allocations per time-unit per call — `Enum.ToString()` does reflection + boxing, then `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates a second string. At millions of calls, this is substantial GC pressure.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`
**Fix:** Cache unit names in a static array indexed by the enum value.

```csharp
// Before (L173-177)
private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant();
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}

// After
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
    ["year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = s_unitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

#### 2. LINQ chains on hot path — 13 call sites allocating enumerators + delegates 🔴
**Impact:** Each LINQ operator allocates an enumerator object + a delegate (for lambda). The `Humanize()` path hits ~5-6 LINQ calls; `DefaultCollectionFormatter` hits ~5-6 more. This is 10-15+ allocations per call beyond the actual work.
**Files:**
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128` — `.Any()` with lambda
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L140,143,146` — `.Where().Take().Where()` chain
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L149` — `[.. timeParts]` materializes the deferred chain
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L158` — `.Where().ToList()`
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L169,284` — `.Take()` for all-but-last
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L244,261-262,270-271` — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chains
- `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L304` — `.Aggregate()` with delegate

**Fix:** Replace LINQ with `foreach` loops. Example for the most impactful sites:

```csharp
// Before (L127-128) — IsContainingOnlyNullValue
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(IEnumerable<string?> timeParts) =>
    !timeParts.Any(x => x != null);

// After — zero-allocation check on the List<string?> we already have
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

```csharp
// Before (L133-149) — SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    IEnumerable<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    if (!countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    timeParts = timeParts.Take(precision);
    if (countEmptyUnits)
        timeParts = timeParts.Where(x => x != null);
    return [.. timeParts];
}

// After — single-pass, zero LINQ
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int taken = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (taken >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) taken++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) taken++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

```csharp
// Before (L266-272) — HumanizeDisplayStrings
var itemsArray = strings
    .Select(item => item == null ? string.Empty : item.Trim())
    .Where(item => !string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(item))
    .ToArray();

// After — single-pass into pre-sized list
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        var trimmed = item?.Trim();
        if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(trimmed))
            items.Add(trimmed);
    }
    // ... rest unchanged using items instead of itemsArray
}
```

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` allocates an array per call 🟡
**Impact:** Every `Transform()` call allocates a `T[]`, even for the common single-transformer case. Impactful if applied per log entry.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`
**Fix:** Add 1-arg overload for the common case:

```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);

// Keep the params overload for 2+ transformers
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, params IStringTransformer[] transformers) =>
    transformers.Aggregate(input, (current, t) => t.Transform(current));
```

#### 4. `DefaultCollectionFormatter` is unsealed with virtual methods 🟡
**Impact:** 5 virtual methods cannot be devirtualized by the JIT. Sealing enables devirtualization and potential inlining. 0 of 1 classes are sealed.
**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L208`
**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword — `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`
